{"id":"astro-ph/0012249","submitter":"Mauro Giavalisco","authors":"Mauro Giavalisco, Mark Dickinson (Space Telescope Science Institute)","title":"Clustering Segregation With UV Luminosity in Lyman-Break Galaxies at z~3\n  and Its Implications","comments":"Corrected a few typos and added a reference. 36 pages, 8 figures,\n  Latex, AAS macros, to appear on the Astrophysical Journal","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1086/319715","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We report on the clustering properties of Lyman-break galaxies (LBGs) at z~3.\nThe correlation length of flux-limited samples of LBGs depends on their\nrest-frame ultraviolet (UV) luminosity at lambda ~1700 Angstrom, with fainter\ngalaxies being less strongly clustered in space. It decreases by a factor ~3\nover the range of limiting magnitudes that we have probed, namely 25<R<27,\nsuggesting that fainter samples include galaxies with smaller mass. We find\nthat: 1) the clustering strength of LBGs follows, within the errors, the same\nscaling law with the volume density predicted for cold dark matter (CDM) halos;\n2) the scaling law predicted for the galaxies using the halos mass spectrum and\na number of models for the relationship that maps the halos' mass into the\ngalaxies' UV luminosity depends only on how tightly mass and UV luminosity\ncorrelate, but is otherwise insensitive to the details of the models. These\nresults provide additional evidence that the strong spatial clustering of LBGs\nis due to galaxy biasing, supporting biased galaxy formation and gravitational\ninstability as the primary mechanism for the formation of structure. We also\nfind that 1) a scale invariant relationship between mass and UV luminosity\n(e.g. a power law) is not supported, suggesting that the properties of star\nformation of galaxies change along the mass spectrum of the observed LBGs; 2)\nthe scatter of the UV luminosity of LBGs of given mass must be relatively small\nfor massive LBGs, suggesting that the mass is an important parameter in\nregulating the activity of star formation in these systems, and that the\nfraction of massive halos at z~3 that are not observed in UV-selected surveys\nis not large.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 12 Dec 2000 00:00:08 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 20 Dec 2000 23:56:07 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
